Remark.Remarks: NRHFD Q225 and M225 were dispatched to an 85 y/o female with a medical emergency. Crews arrived and were briefed by members of NRHPD. The patient was assessed, moved to the cot, and taken to the MICU. The patient was detained under a mental app by NRHPD. Vitals were assessed and transport was initiated to JPS by M225. Q225 remained on scene and ensured that the patients husband would be able to care for himself. He demonstrated to us that he could call 911 and refused any assistance. Q225 cleared and returned to service. M225 transported without incident and returned to service.

Remark.Remarks: Quint 221 and Medic 223 responded to a 78 year old male that was at home and family stated that they could not take care of him at least for the night. Family stated that earlier in the day that he was having hallucinations and acting combative. The caregiver that was there earlier in the day stated that he was also being very mean and tried to kick her earlier. That particular caregiver was not there at the time when we were called. When we arrived the patient was walking around the patio with his walker and stated that he was fine. When we arrived, he was very cooperative and basically stated that he did not want to go to the hospital. One of the issues that we were having was that the sister stated that she could not take care him, due to his issues. The caretakers were not willing to stay so there was no one going to be at the residence with him overnight and we could not let him stay alone by himself even though he thought he could. Pt was incontinent at this time and was still not willing to go. After speaking to the family and the caregivers it was clear that no one was going to stay with the patient. Quint 221 personnel then went out and told the patient that he was going to have to go to the hospital and be observed. The sister was well informed that she needed to get with the case workers at the facility and try and find some other arrangements for him until family was able to return from North Carolina to take care of the patient. There were several attempts made to try and contact the wife who was in North Carolina, however, we were not able to contact the female during the time we were there. The patient reluctantly chose to go with us. His sister stated that she was going to go to the hospital so that she could hopefully make other arrangements for him. Patient was then transported to Baylor Grapevine for further evaluation. Quint 221 then cleared the scene.

Remark.Remarks: Quint 221 and Medic 221 responded to a 58 year old male that was in cardiac arrest. We arrived on the scene to find a 58 year old male that was sitting in a chair in far back room. Upon our arrival, the male was unresponsive and cyanotic. CPR was initiated, while in the chair. The patient was a large male and there was lot of stuff in the home which caused some difficulty in moving the patient out to the cot. Patient was placed on a sheet to move him to an area where we could begin proper ALS procedures. As soon, as available patient was then placed on the Lucas device and backboard. Patient was then moved onto the cot and wheeled out to the ambulance. Once in the back of the ambulance Medic 221 began to perform ALS procedures. Patient was then transported to North Hills for further care and evaluation. Quint 221, remained out of service until personnel will reunited with the unit. Quint 221 then cleared the scene.
